title: Large pre-equilibrium contribution in A + nat.Ni interactions at ~ 8-40 MeV

x4freetext: Large pre-equilibrium contribution in A + nat.Ni
interactions at ~ 8-40 MeV

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.78, p.044606 (2008)

x4codes.hlp: Variable Energy Cyclotron Centre, Kolkata, India

x4freetext: The natural Ni samples (prepared by rolling) of
thickness ~3.32 mg/cm**2 (measured by the
alpha-transmission method) were pasted into
aluminium holders.
Various standard sources of known strength
were used to determine the efficiency of the
detector at various source-detector separations. The
sample-detector separations were suitably adjusted
to minimize the dead time to <10 %.
An excitation functions for A + nat.Ni
have been measured by using the stacked foil
activation technique followed by off-line gamma-ray
spectrometry.
A collimated alpha beam ~40 MeV has been allowed to
fall on a stack of eight targets for ~12 hours with a
beam current ~100 nA. Post-irradiation analysis has
been performed by using high resolution, large volume
(100 c.c.), precalibrated HPGe detector coupled with
a data-acquisition system.
The evaporation residues were identified by
their characteristic gamma-ray energies, half-lives
and branching ratios. Area under the peaks of
identified gamma-lines of evaporation residues were
used to compute the experimentally measured
cross-sections. The experimentally measured Efs are
compared with the calculations performed with the
theoretical model code ALICE-91, which takes both
equilibrium and pre-equilibrium (PE) decay processes
into account. The CN calculations in this code are
performed by using the Weisskopf-Ewing model, whereas
the PE component is simulated by using the
geometry- dependent hybrid model.
The geometry-dependent effciency of gamma-ray
counting at various source-detector separations has
been deduced and fitted with fourth-order polynomial
function, where the uncertainty from the fitting is
found to be < (or =) 3%.
The errors in efficiency on account of the
solid-angle effect have been found to be < (or =) 2%.
The errors expected in the number of nuclei
on account of the non-uniform thickness of the sample
may be deduced by measuring the thickness at
different positions of the sample and are found to
The error from the fluctuations in the beam
current was found to be ~3%.
During irradiation of the stack, the beam
traverses the thickness of the material , thus
reducing the initial beam intensity. It
is estimated that the error from this decrease in
beam intensity is < (or = )2%.
The overall errors in the present
measurement are found to be < (or =) 15%.

M. S. University of Baroda and Dr. S. Ganesan of
Reactor Physics Design Division, B.A.R.C, Mumbai.
